Unless you use parentheses, brackets, braces or a backslash, Python lines end with the newline character. The following text is three separate lines that show the same error:

```
str_ = &quot;A&quot;
+ &quot;B&quot;
+ &quot;C&quot;
```

You can extend lines using a backslash:

```
str_ = &quot;A&quot; \
+ &quot;B&quot; \
+ &quot;C&quot;
```

You can also group with parentheses:

```
str_ = (&quot;A&quot;
+ &quot;B&quot;
+ &quot;C&quot;)
```

If all the components of the string are literals, you don&#39;t even need the `+` operator: neighboring string literals are concatenated automatically:

```
str_ = (&quot;A&quot;
&quot;B&quot;
&quot;C&quot;)
```

Another way to concatenate strings is interpolation. This is generally useful when your components are variables of arbitrary type. You can do something like

```
a = &quot;A&quot;
b = &quot;B&quot;
c = &quot;C&quot;
str_ = f&#39;{a}{b}{c}&#39;
```

